## Header Findings

| Header | Value | Analysis |
|---------|-------|----------|
| From | alerts@chase.com | Appears legitimate |
| Reply-To | kellyellin426@proton.me | Suspicious |
| Return-Path | kellyellin426@proton.me | Suspicious |
| Sender IP | 185.70.40.140 | Proton Mail Infrastructure |
| Reverse DNS | 185-70-40-140.protonmail.ch | Proton Mail |
| SPF | PASS | Sender authenticated as ProtonMail |
| DKIM | None | Cannot verify Chase authenticity |
| DMARC | None | Missing authentication |

---

## Why is this suspicious?

Although the email appears to originate from **alerts@chase.com**, both the **Reply-To** and **Return-Path** headers point to a Proton Mail account.

Legitimate financial institutions generally do not redirect replies to personal Proton Mail accounts.

The sender IP also belongs to Proton Mail rather than Chase Bank.

---

## SPF Analysis

![SPF](Screenshots/SPF_checker.png)

SPF validation **passed**.

However, SPF only verifies that the message was sent from a server authorized for the **sending domain** (Proton Mail).

It **does not verify** that the sender actually belongs to Chase Bank.

Attackers frequently abuse trusted email providers such as Proton Mail or Gmail to send phishing emails.

---

## Header Verdict

Multiple header anomalies indicate sender impersonation.

Indicators include:

- Reply-To mismatch
- Return-Path mismatch
- Proton Mail infrastructure
- Missing DKIM authentication
- Missing DMARC protection

These findings significantly increase confidence that the email is fraudulent.

